Here's how to implement all three in your `EditProductPage`:

**1 & 2. Intercept back navigation and confirm:**

Override `OnBackButtonPressed` (hardware/gesture back) and hook into Shell's `Navigating` event:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    private bool _hasUnsavedChanges;

    protected override void OnAppearing()
    {
        base.OnAppearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating += OnShellNavigating;
    }

    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        Shell.Current.Navigating -= OnShellNavigating;
    }

    // Intercepts Shell navigation (including toolbar back button)
    private async void OnShellNavigating(object sender, ShellNavigatingEventArgs e)
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return;

        var deferral = e.GetDeferral();

        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!leave)
            e.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }

    // Intercepts Android/device hardware back button
    protected override bool OnBackButtonPressed()
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
            return base.OnBackButtonPressed();

        MainThread.BeginInvokeOnMainThread(async () =>
        {
            bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (leave)
            {
                _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
                await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            }
        });

        return true; // true = we handled it, suppress default behavior
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button:**

Replace Shell's default back arrow with a toolbar item:

```csharp
// In OnAppearing or constructor
Shell.SetBackButtonBehavior(this, new BackButtonBehavior
{
    TextOverride = "Cancel",
    Command = new Command(async () =>
    {
        if (!_hasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
            return;
        }

        bool leave = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (leave)
        {
            _hasUnsavedChanges = false;
            await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
        }
    })
});
```

Or declaratively in XAML:

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
</ContentPage>
```

**Key points:**
- **`ShellNavigatingEventArgs.GetDeferral()`** lets you go async before deciding to cancel — this is what makes the confirmation dialog possible.
- **`OnBackButtonPressed`** only fires for the Android hardware/gesture back; `Shell.Navigating` covers the toolbar back button.
- **`BackButtonBehavior`** replaces the default arrow; when you set a `Command`, it overrides the default navigation so you control it entirely.
